{"root":{"children":[{"type":"html","html":"<p class='u-drop-cap--line'>

When I was transitioning between high school and my first year of college, I created a zine. I was armed with a typewriter my great aunt had owned, a glue stick and some plain white letter paper. There was a Kinkos nearby for production of my little publication. I named the zine Martha Dumptruck, after the picked-on character in the movie Heathers. The cover was a picture of DIY lo-fi hero Lou Barlow that I lifted from the album The Freed Man (which later got warped from sitting too long in the sun — one of the perils of vinyl ownership). The contents consisted of a fake interview with the cover star conducted via a magic 8-ball, some record reviews and an address where anyone who shared the sensibilities of the zine could write to me.
</p>"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"During my second semester of college, I developed a lump in my chest that would initially be dismissed as just my sternum, but would later be diagnosed as lymphoma. I had to start treatment at Duke Medical Center immediately after my diagnosis and drop out of East Carolina University a few weeks short of the end of the semester. Grades had to wait while I got some unwanted spare time. I needed something to focus on, apart from my cancer treatment.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1},{"type":"paywall"},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"During my chemo, I had books to read and records to listen to, but I required a creative outlet. I turned back to zine making, and produced a second issue of Martha Dumptruck to drop off at record stores. This time, my writing improved a bit (though it was still pretty atrocious). I never got any letters from the people out there who may have picked up a copy of the zine at the record stores where I left it, but it's fair to say I was hooked on self-publishing. When tools for self-publishing on the internet started maturing, I relished the ability to easily write for others. Blogger's slogan "push-button publishing" strongly resonated with me. It really was as simple as they made it sound.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"I've found myself very attracted to indie software that lets an independent developer shape the course of their vision for users. Many times, the resulting software is perfect for independent users, who then adopt that same vision or fit their usage needs into the constraints. The last few years, I've been using the Micro.blog hosted blogging service to publish most of my words. The service has been a great way to write in my app of choice — several apps on the Mac support publishing to Micro.blog — and get my thoughts out to people who theoretically want to read blog posts. As Micro.blog got more functionality, it became easier to customize your blog and make it your online home. When there were issues, you could reach out to the developer, Manton Reece, and get help. Unfortunately, Micro.blog has grown in functionality, it has also increased in bugs and surface area to cover.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Micro.blog is in a difficult place right now. It still only has the one full-time developer, but as it gains in users (particularly in light of the recent changes at Twitter) it also has more surface area to support. It's starting to seem like more than one person can handle. However, it's probably not yet in a place where it is bringing in enough revenue to be able to bring in another developer or someone to provide support.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1},{"type":"image","src":"__GHOST_URL__/content/images/2022/11/thinking-of-micro.blog.jpeg","title":"thinkingblog","caption":""},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Late in the summer, I was at the beach and had some time on my hands to fiddle with the theme of my blog (this is what I do when I get a vacation). Unfortunately, I ran into problems with Micro.blog, where CSS variables wouldn't work, and my blog ended up in an in-between two themes state and looked pretty janky. I emailed help to see if I could get some assistance on the strange issues. At the same time, I ran into an issue with HEY email where the "focus and reply" functionality would work on my iPad. I emailed HEY at roughly the same time I emailed Micro.blog. I heard back from a super friendly HEY support rep the next day, and the bug was fixed within a week. It was two weeks before I heard anything back from Micro.blog and my issue was unresolved. It persists to this day, but I've used media queries and hard-coded values to work around it in most cases.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"During the past weekend, I ran into multiple bugs in Micro.blog. My newsletter took 11 hours to send. I tried to add my newsletter sign-up to my posts page, and it massively messed up the interface, for no apparent reason. I tried to switch themes to test my changes in another theme, and my blog got stuck in between themes and had elements of both, causing it to look really strange. The attempt to use the new feature to import posts to my blog via RSS from HEY World and the stylesheets on the post didn't work (ultimately, this was an issue with the HTML in the HEY World post).","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"You can like and admire an independent software publisher, but the software still needs to work. ","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"aside","version":1},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"They say that in order to write well, "show, don't tell." Since I don't know how to show interesting bug reports (at least not in this format — I was a QA Manager for 10 years), I'll spare you additional details. This could get to be a pretty dry post. My point is that, if you're the sole developer of Micro.blog, you're going to want to focus on what your users want most. Right now, with the social media scene in the midst of a long-overdue fragmentation, that's interoperability with Mastodon. Many Micro.blog users, new and old, are testing this connectivity out. Meanwhile, though, whole features, like the newsletter, for which people pay a premium, ","type":"text","version":1},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"are not working","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"link","rel":null,"target":null,"title":null,"url":"https://help.micro.blog/t/newsletter-not-sending/1251","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":" at all for some. Like any software product owner, you are going to decide to spend your resources where they are the most impactful. As I used to say all the time in my professional life, "it's a consumption choice."","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Every software feature has a total cost of ownership that doesn't end at the implementation of the feature. The cost of maintenance can be even higher than the price tag of initial development. If you don't keep this reality in mind, you may find yourself in over your head with a burden of support that is too great to bear. While it may be more fun and exciting to develop new features than fix bugs, and may even bring in more users, it can end up being at the expense of your existing user base.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1},{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Maybe I take all of this a bit too seriously for casual software. None of what I said is meant to apply to professional, mission-critical infrastructure. As I've said before though, regarding blogging, ","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":2,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"this is my hobby","type":"text","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":". When you golf, you want the best clubs for the way you play your game, even if it is just a recreational activity for most.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1}],"direction":"ltr","format":"","indent":0,"type":"root","version":1}}
